\layout Title

Lattice models and fractal measures
\layout Author

Linas Vepstas <linas@linas.org>
\layout Date

15 September 2006 (updated 30 September 2006)
\layout Abstract

This paper reviews connections between the Bernoulli map, the baker's map
 and the Ising model.
 The Bernoulli map is possibly the simplest exactly solvable model of determinis
tic chaos.
 Its Frobenius-Perron operator or transfer operator has a set of well-known
 polynomial eigenvectors, given by the Bernoulli polynomials.
 Its also has a set of smooth but non-integrable eigenvectors given by the
 Hurwitz zeta function.
 Alternately, it has a set of fractal eigenvectors, of which the Blancmange
 or Takagi curve is one.
\layout Abstract

An even larger set of functions that are eigenvectors of the Bernoulli operator
 may be obtained by considering a one dimensional lattice model, such as
 the Ising model.
 Functions that are translationally invariant on a one-dimensional lattice
 are nothing more or less than eigenvectors of the Bernoulli operator with
 eigenvalue one.
 These functions, when graphed on the real number line, are in general not
 even continuous.
 
\layout Abstract

Functins that are continuous-nowhere are traditionally considered to be
 intractible, and usually, very little can be said about them.
 By identifying them with a set of simple, tractable operations on a one-dimensi
onal lattice model, one obtains a set of tools with which to manipulate
 and analyze such functions.
\layout Abstract

A notable example of a discontinuouis-everywhere function that is not traditiona
lly integrable, yet, when properly defined, can be integrated, is derivative
 of the Minkowski question mark function.
 It, and its generalizations are known as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

multi-fractal measures
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

.
 Thus, this paper explores what it means to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

take the derivative of the question mark function
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

.
 As a side-effect, all of the various functions that occur have a particular
 fractal self-symmetry, which can be made explicitly manifest; it is the
 symmetry of the dyadic monoid, that is, the period-doubling subset of the
 modular group 
\begin_inset Formula $SL(2,\mathbb{Z})$
\end_inset 

.
