\layout Subsubsection

Fractal self-symmetry
\layout Standard

In this section, we want to give explicit expression to the apparent fractal
 self-similarity seen in the Ising model.
 To simplify the discussion, this section assumes the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $N\to\infty$
\end_inset 

, or at least that 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset 

 is indeterminate when the 
\begin_inset Formula $N\to\infty$
\end_inset 

 limit is ambiguous or ill-defined.
 As before, the lattice is assumed to be one-sided: that is, it starts at
 0 and stretches off to the right, so that lattice positions can be labelled
 by non-negative integers.
 The two-sided lattice is treated in a later section; while there are many
 similarities, there are also important differences between the one-sided
 and the two sided lattice.
\layout Standard

Consider the behavior of the classical Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Classical Hamiltonian}

\end_inset 

 under the right shift of the lattice, with a new spin 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset 

 introduced to occupy the zeroth position.
 One then has 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
H(s,\sigma_{0},\sigma_{1},\sigma_{2},\cdots)=V(s,\sigma_{0},\sigma_{1},\sigma_{2},\cdots)+H(\sigma_{0},\sigma_{1},\sigma_{2},\cdots)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 Taking 
\begin_inset Formula $s=-1$
\end_inset 

 and using the dyadic mapping 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:dyadic map}

\end_inset 

, the above may be written as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
H\left(\frac{x}{2}\right)=V\left(\frac{x}{2}\right)+H\left(x\right)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 while for 
\begin_inset Formula $s=+1$
\end_inset 

 one has 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
H\left(\frac{1+x}{2}\right)=V\left(\frac{1+x}{2}\right)+H\left(x\right)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 For the probability distribution, one has (after taking 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{B}=T=1$
\end_inset 

) 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
P\left(\frac{x}{2}\right)=e^{-V(x/2)}P\left(x\right)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 and so on.
 As any true self-similarity, this can be iterated repeatedly, so that 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
P\left(\frac{x}{2^{n}}\right)=P(x)\;\prod_{k=1}^{n}e^{-V(x/2^{k})}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 For the Ising potential 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Ising potential}

\end_inset 

, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $V(x)$
\end_inset 

 takes a particularly simple form: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
V_{\mbox{Ising}}(x)=\begin{cases}
J-M & \quad\mbox{ for }0\le x<\frac{1}{4}\\
-J-M & \quad\mbox{ for }\frac{1}{4}\le x<\frac{1}{2}\\
-J+M & \quad\mbox{ for }\frac{1}{2}\le x<\frac{3}{4}\\
J+M & \quad\mbox{ for }\frac{3}{4}\le x\le1\end{cases}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 and so the probability distribution has a simple scaling:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
P_{\mbox{Ising}}\left(\frac{x}{2^{n}}\right)=\lambda^{n}P_{\mbox{Ising}}(x)\qquad\mbox{for }0\le x\le\frac{1}{2}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=\exp(M-J)$
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

Another natural symmetry operation of the lattice is the exchange of spin
 values 
\begin_inset Formula $+\sigma_{k}\leftrightarrow-\sigma_{k}$
\end_inset 

.
 For the dyadic mapping, this corresponds to the exchange 
\begin_inset Formula $x\leftrightarrow1-x$
\end_inset 

.
 Let the exchange of spin values be denoted by the operation 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset 

 (for 
\emph on 
reflection
\emph default 
); the dyadic representation of 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset 

 is the function 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{D}(x)=1-x$
\end_inset 

.
 Let the right shift operation, with an insertion of a spin of -1 at the
 zeroth lattice position be denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset 

.
 The dyadic representation of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset 

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{D}(x)=x/2$
\end_inset 

.
 The operations 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset 

, taken as a free monoid (that is a free group, but with non-negative powers
 only) generate the dyadic monoid.
 A synopsis of the properties of this monoid are given below, after which
 the analysis of self-similarity resumes.
\layout Subsubsection

The dyadic monoid
\layout Standard

Given operations 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset 

 acting as representations of translation and reflection, one has in essence
 constructed everything that is needed to have a fractal with dyadic symmetry.
 That is, one need only to recognize that 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset 

 generate the dyadic monoid of the modular group 
\begin_inset Formula $SL(2,\mathbb{Z})$
\end_inset 

.
 The elements of this monoid are of the form
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\gamma=g^{a}rg^{b}rg^{c}\cdots\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c,\ldots$
\end_inset 

 are non-negative integers.
 This section provides a very brief synopsis of the general properties of
 monoid elements 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset 

; these properties are presented in greater detail in 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Ve-M04,Ve-T04}

\end_inset 

.
 First, all such elements may be represented by the continued fraction
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\gamma_{C}=\frac{1}{a+\frac{1}{b+\frac{1}{c+\cdots}}}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 Since every real number has an (essentially) unique representation in terms
 of continued fractions (up to a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}_{2}$
\end_inset 

choice), this means the self-symmetries of the fractal may be labelled by
 the real numbers.
 The generators 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset 

 also generate walks on the infinite binary tree: 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset 

 may be taken to mean 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

always take the left branch
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset 

 may be taken to mean 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

reverse the sense of left and right
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

.
 Walks on the binary tree may also be represented as a sequence of left,
 right moves.
 An arbitrary string in two letters 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset 

 and R may be taken to be a real number as well, which may be denoted by
 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{D}$
\end_inset 

 when the sequence of 
\begin_inset Formula $L,R$
\end_inset 

 moves take one to the same place as the series of 
\begin_inset Formula $g,r$
\end_inset 

 moves given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{C}$
\end_inset 

.
 That is, one has the representation as a binary fraction
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\gamma_{D}=\begin{array}{ccccc}
0.\underbrace{000...0} & \underbrace{11..1} & \underbrace{00..0} & \underbrace{11..1} & \underbrace{00..0}1..\\
a-1 & b & c & d & e\end{array}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $L=0$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R=1$
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

The Minkowski question mark function is nothing more and nothing less than
 the function that relates 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{C}$
\end_inset 

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{D}$
\end_inset 

.
 That is,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
?(\gamma_{C})=\gamma_{D}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 In terms of the generators, on has 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x)=1-r(1-x)$
\end_inset 

, which is satisfied by the question mark: 
\begin_inset Formula $(?\circ r)(x)=?(1-x)=1-?(x)=(r\circ?)(x)$
\end_inset 

.
 The generator 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset 

 has inequivalent representations 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{D}$
\end_inset 

and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{C}$
\end_inset 

 for the dyadic and continued fraction representations, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{D}(x)=x/2$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{C}(x)=x/(x+1)$
\end_inset 

, so that one has 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left(g_{D}\circ?\right)(x)=\frac{?(x)}{2}=?\left(\frac{x}{x+1}\right)=\left(?\circ g_{C}\right)(x)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 To summarize, a general monoid element 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=g^{a}rg^{b}rg^{c}\cdots$
\end_inset 

 has two inequivalent representations as a real number.
 
\layout Standard

Another important property is that both 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{D}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{C}$
\end_inset 

 can also be understood to be maps from the unit interval to a specific
 subinterval.
 This, for example,
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\gamma_{D}(x)=(g_{D}^{a_{1}}r_{D}g_{D}^{a_{2}}r_{D}...r_{D}g_{D}^{a_{N}})(x)=\frac{1}{2^{a_{1}}}-\frac{1}{2^{a_{1}+a_{2}}}+\frac{1}{2^{a_{1}+a_{2}+a_{3}}}-...+(-)^{N+1}\frac{x}{2^{a_{1}+a_{2}+a_{3}+...+a_{N}}}\label{eq:interval map}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 maps the unit interval into a dyadic sub-interval.
 Use of continued fractions gives another, different interval map for 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{C}$
\end_inset 

.
\layout Subsubsection

Self-similarity again
\layout Standard

Returning to the self-symmetries of the classical lattice models, one can
 write transformation properties of the probability distribution as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left(P\circ g_{D}\right)(x)=P\left(\frac{x}{2}\right)=e^{-V(x/2)}P\left(x\right)=e^{-\left(V\circ g_{D}\right)(x)}P(x)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left(P\circ r\right)(x)=P\left(1-x\right)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 One may now ask for, and provide, the self-similarity transformation that
 corresponds to the interval map 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:interval map}

\end_inset 

.
 The iterated application of the above two equations then provides a formula
 that relates the probability distribution on a sub-interval to the probability
 distribution on the entire interval.
\layout Standard

The simpler case, treated first, occurs when the potential is symmetric
 under the exchange of 
\begin_inset Formula $+\sigma_{k}\leftrightarrow-\sigma_{k}$
\end_inset 

; that is, when 
\begin_inset Formula $V(x)=V(1-x)$
\end_inset 

.
 One may then easily show that 
\begin_inset Formula $P(x)=P(1-x)$
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard

Consider, for example, the interval given by 
\begin_inset Formula $grg^{3}(x)=\frac{1}{2}-\frac{x}{8}$
\end_inset 

.
 Then, repeatedly applying the above, one obtains 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
P\left(\frac{1}{2}-\frac{x}{8}\right) & = & P\left(grg^{3}\right)\nonumber \\
 & = & e^{-V(grg^{3})}P\left(rg^{3}\right)\nonumber \\
 & = & e^{-V(grg^{3})}P\left(g^{3}\right)\nonumber \\
 & = & e^{-V(grg^{3})}e^{-V(g^{3})}e^{-V(g^{2})}e^{-V(g)}P\left(x\right)\label{eq:}\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset 

 where the argument 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset 

 was dropped to keep the notation simple.
 This formula relates in a precise (and computable) way the probability
 distribution on a subinterval to the whole interval.
 The process can be repeated to obtain a relation joining any dyadic subinterval
 to the whole interval.
 
\layout Standard

For potentials that are not symmetric, the development has some additional
 complications.
 Write the potential as in terms of even and odd parts 
\begin_inset Formula $V(x)=V_{e}(x)+V_{o}(x)$
\end_inset 

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{e}(x)=V_{e}(1-x)$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{o}(x)=-V_{o}(1-x)$
\end_inset 

.
 It follows from equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Classical Hamiltonian}

\end_inset 

 that the energy can be decomposed in the same way.
 The probability is multiplicative, so one has 
\begin_inset Formula $P(x)=P_{e}(x)P_{o}(x)$
\end_inset 

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{e}(x)=\exp(-H_{e}(x))$
\end_inset 

 and similarly for 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{o}$
\end_inset 

.
 Under inversion , one then has 
\begin_inset Formula $P(1-x)=P_{e}(x)/P_{o}(x)$
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard

The point here is that the probability distribution has a self-similar structure
, one might say a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

covariant
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 structure, under the action of the dyadic monoid.
 The generators of the monoid correspond to a right-shift on the one-sided
 lattice, and the inversion of spins.
 
\layout Standard

-----------------
\layout Standard

The Ising model interaction potential has the general form 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
V(\sigma_{0},\sigma_{1},\sigma_{2},\cdots)=\sigma_{0}f(\sigma_{1},\sigma_{2},\cdots)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 for some general function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset 

 of the lattice spins 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{1},\sigma_{2},\cdots$
\end_inset 

.
 Using the dyadic mapping , this condition implies that 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
V\left(\frac{1+x}{2}\right)=-V\left(\frac{x}{2}\right)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

In addition, for 
\begin_inset Formula $M=0$
\end_inset 

, the Ising model potential has symmetry under the exchange of 
