 gives a cumulative probability distribution that is exactly the question
 mark function.
 There is not just one, but several interactions that give such a cumulative
 distribution.
 One may obtained by a simple, explicit manipulation.
 The other is hinted at numerically, under the name of the Kac model, given
 below.
\layout Standard

Suppose one wants to have 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
P(x)=\left(?^{\prime}\circ?^{-1}\right)(x)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 exactly.
 One may then work backwards to find the potential, as follows.
 One must have 
\begin_inset Formula $P(?(x))=?^{\prime}(x)$
\end_inset 

, and, applying the symmetries of the question mark function,
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{?(x)}{2}=?\left(\frac{x}{1+x}\right)\label{eq:question-self}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

one has simply that 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
P\left(\frac{?(x)}{2}\right)=P\left(?\left(\frac{x}{1+x}\right)\right)=?^{\prime}\left(\frac{x}{1+x}\right)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 Applying the symmetry of the lattice model under the action of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset 

 as discussed above, one gets an expression involving the potential 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
P\left(\frac{?(x)}{2}\right)=\exp\left(-V\left(\frac{?(x)}{2}\right)\right)P\left(?(x)\right)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

