\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

dust
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 or density is given by the transfer operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset 

 as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left[\mathcal{L}\rho\right](x,y)=\left(\rho\circ\tau^{-1}\right)(x,y)=\rho\left(2x-\left\lfloor 2x\right\rfloor \,,\,\frac{y+\left\lfloor 2x\right\rfloor }{2}\right)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 The transfer operator is thus a map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}:\mathcal{F}\to\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset 

 is the set of functions on the unit square.
 Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset 

 is a linear operator.
 One is interested in characterizing the eigenfunctions and eigenvalues
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset 

.
 The general idea behind equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Classical Hamiltonian}

\end_inset 

