Free monoids and the self-symmetries of lattices
\layout Standard

The set of strings generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $g,r$
\end_inset 

 is the free monoid 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{N}\times\mathbb{Z}_{2}$
\end_inset 

, the monoid analog of a free group.
 The notation here is that the exponent on 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset 

 is any element of the natural numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset 

 while 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}_{2}$
\end_inset 

 indicates that exponent on 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset 

 is 0 or 1 because 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{2}=e$
\end_inset 

.
 The Cayley graph of this monoid is the infinite binary tree, and, as mentioned
 above, it is shared by the monoid 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{N}\times\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset 

 when interpreted as sequences of left-right moves walking the tree.
 That is, the monoid generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{N}\times\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset 

 is the set of all strings in two letters.
\layout Standard

It should be clear from the above construction that the 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset 

-state lattice model, of which the Potts model is an example, would have
 a set of symmetries that are the free monoid of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{N}\times\mathbb{Z}_{K}$
\end_inset 

.
 (Properly, the symmetries are isometries, although the 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset 

-adic metric has not yet been defined here.) The point here is that the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

ordinary
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 Euclidean translations are not the only symmetries that occur naturally
 in the studies of lattice models.
 
\layout Standard

Now, in general, when some function on a topological space has some self-resembl
ance after some action, one says that this function is self-similar.
 When there are a countable number of such self-resemblances, one might
 say that the function is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

translationally invariant
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

, or so, or show that a fixed point results.
 When the number of such self-resemblances is dense in some way, or tends
 to the uncountable, or is characterized by a free group or free monoid,
 one says the function is a fractal.
 This motivates the following definition of a fractal:
\layout Description

Definition Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset 

 be topological spaces, and 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset 

 be some map between them.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho:X\to X$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau:X\to X$
\end_inset 

 be two isomorphisms of the spaces.
 The map 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset 

 is said to preserves these isomorphisms, if there exist maps 
\begin_inset Formula $r:Y\to Y$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g:Y\to Y$
\end_inset 

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ\rho=r\circ f$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ\tau=g\circ f$
\end_inset 

.
 If such an 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset 

 exists, and if 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset 

 together generate some free monid, then we say that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset 

 has the 
\series bold 
\emph on 
structure of a fractal
\series default 
\emph default 
.
\layout Standard

This definition seems almost silly, because after a bit of reflection, one
 realizes that there are many, many systems in physics and mathematics that
 would have the structure of a fractal according to this definition.
 For example, every Lie group has a discrete lattice that acts freely on
 the Lie group, and thus one may find maps that have the structure of a
 fractal.
 On the other hand, this is perhaps not unexpected: the Anosov flow on the
 tangent space of a Lie group typically has expanding and contracting directions
, making the tangent manifold hyperbolic, and the flow ergodic.
 Ergodicity is typically associated with fractal behaviour, and hyperbolic
 structures typically admit ergodic flows, and so the above definition of
 a fractal structure is perhaps not ludicrous.
 
\layout Standard

The requirement that 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset 

