We can use sigma additivity to construct a collection of translation invariant
 measures as follows.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(C_{(n,A)})=x$
\end_inset 

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le x\le1$
\end_inset 

.
 Then sigma-additivity requires that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(C_{(n,B)})=1-x$
\end_inset 

 which follows from the fact that the union of these two disjoint sets is
 the entire space.
 One may readily deduce that 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mu(C_{(n,s)})=x^{\# A(s)}(1-x)^{\# B(s)}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\# A(s)$
\end_inset 

 is the number of times the letter 'A' occurs in the string ''s'', and likewise
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\# B(s)$
\end_inset 

.
 In most physics applications, the canonical and symmetric choice would
 be 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1/2$
\end_inset 

, but it should be clear that this is not mathematically constrained.
 One might even be able to make physical arguments to have ''x'' be something
 other than one-half, if, for example (and maybe a bad example), some external
 force is causing there to be more spins pointing in one direction than
 the other, on average.
 
